And, of course, very selective. I can still remember finding out about the secret meetings which were held in London, open only to some &#039;comrades&#039;. The decision to &#039;dissolve&#039; the group wasn&#039;t embarked on democratically or openly, but pursued behind the backs of quite a few members. And, of course, putting out issue 73 and subsequent claims that CW was no more did no favours to those who didn&#039;t share your analysis and felt there was life yet in the CW beast.

The strangest thing about the split in &#039;97 in retrospect is the disappearance from active class struggle politics of so many of the then members who promised so much would emerge from Smash Hits and Bradford 98. People in London who remained within CW have since been heavily involved with groups like MA&#039;M, Fitwatch, the Whitechapel Anarchist Group and now ALARM. We&#039;ve brought the CW way of doing things to a new generation of people, both within and outside &#039;the movement&#039;. By contrast, those who sought to dissolve CW have themselves been conspicuous by their absence since Bradford 98.
